Rest In Peace Mick Rock 

#Repost @paulbui 

Paul Bui had the honor of getting to know Mick, when He creative directed this short documentary about his illustrious 50+ year career. He generously invited him into his New Jersey home, where he spent the day flipping through photo books, recounting personal stories that have now become fabled tales in the cannons of rock music history.
Mick first picked up a camera on an acid trip in Cambridge, which then snowballed into shooting the likes of The Sex Pistols, Lou Reed, Joan Jett, Queen, Blonde and of course his remarkable body of work with David Bowie during those quintessential Ziggy Stardust years. "I shot him in 74 different outfits," Mick candidly shared in this video. "He was like a mosaic." Always embodying the rebellious rock n roll spirt of this era, Mick was so humble, hilarious, open, gracious and truly inspiring to be around….He will be missed.
#mickrock @feralcatpro @therealmickrock 

Directed by the fabulous @lew_is.
Creative Directed by @paulbui
Edited by Katie Hickman
Shot by jose.
cota & Annabel Gonzales

HAPPY BIRTHDAY TO THE HAPPIEST!!
The greatest Daddy, Hubby, Best friend and Jedi Master EVER. 
🕺🏼🎂🥂💕🍟❣️🐝🤩🥃🤓
@mazdackrassi we love you so much. 

Just like a dream!!

HAPPY 11th BIRTHDAY RUMI + JUNO
🎉🎂 💗 💫🧁🥳🌭🌟🎈🤩🎁🦄😻
We couldn’t be prouder of the little ladies you’ve both become. 
Can’t believe we get to be your Mummy + Daddy. 
We love you both SO much!!!!

Mahin Rassi  1934 - 2025

Mom was 91 years young. The most loving and nurturing mother a son could ever ask for.

She taught me how to be a better person—to be kind yet forthright, to be strong yet compassionate. 

She was incredibly resilient and determined. In 1979, after the Iranian Revolution, she made the impossible choice to leave everything behind to give us a better future. She risked everything to get us to America to join our dad and if not for her courage, we would still be in Iran today. She was fearless, always calm in the face of adversity. Nothing phased her. 

When we arrived in the U.S. with little means, she made sure we never felt deprived. No matter how difficult things were, there was always Persian food on the table. When my brother and I longed for American pizza we couldn’t afford, she made her own version—ketchup on Persian bread with sliced hot dogs. It may not have been the real thing but we loved it! 

She worked tirelessly, taking care of us and dad, who was much older than her. Working as a full-time seamstress while also studying to get her second master’s degree. Through it all, she never complained.

She taught me everything. How to be gracious, how to cook without measuring, how to drape and sew my own clothes, how to throw a party, how to lead with passion and give it my all. And, how to never, ever give up.

One of my proudest moments was showing her MILK STUDIOS for the first time. She loved it…but told me not to buy coffee at the café—it was too expensive. It was OUR café. 

My drive to succeed has always been fueled by a desire to regain what was taken from us and to make my parents proud. 

She always wanted daughters - so getting Zanna as her daughter-in-law and becoming Grandma to Jordan, Rumi + Juno made her complete. She passed on her wisdom in every conversation with them. Family was everything to her. And she was everything to us. 

Happy Nowruz Mom, thank you for everything you did for us. 

I will miss you so much. 

Love, your Son, Mazdack
